From 5969626c0a5a9f5a933f02baed4ea62cf3e135ce Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Mykola Lysenko <nickolay.lysenko@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 12 Jul 2026 16:02:38 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 2/5] common/verity: fail loudly when corrupting a file without
 fiemap extents

_fsv_scratch_corrupt_bytes locates file data via fiemap and overwrites
it directly on the block device.  Files whose data is not visible
through fiemap -- notably btrfs inline extents (file size <=
max_inline, default 2048) -- expose no usable physical address, so the
dd silently misses and the caller then "verifies" data that was never
corrupted.

This turned generic/574's block_size=1024 cases into false positives on
btrfs: every read of the supposedly corrupted file succeeded, and the
test reported fs-verity as failing to detect corruption while the
kernel had nothing to detect (confirmed via dmesg: no csum or
verity errors; identical behaviour on 6.x-era and current kernels,
and on both UML and KVM).

Fail the helper loudly instead of corrupting nothing: tests that
corrupt small files must ensure real extents (e.g. btrfs
-o max_inline=0) or use an fs-specific corruption tool.

Signed-off-by: Mykola Lysenko <nickolay.lysenko@gmail.com>
---
 common/verity | 9 +++++++++
 1 file changed, 9 insertions(+)

diff --git a/common/verity b/common/verity
index 11e839d..9140931 100644
--- a/common/verity
+++ b/common/verity
@@ -337,6 +337,15 @@ _fsv_scratch_corrupt_bytes()
 
 	_scratch_sync	# Sync to avoid unwritten extents
 
+	# Inline extents (e.g. btrfs files <= max_inline) expose no usable
+	# physical address via fiemap, so the dd below would silently miss
+	# and the caller would test uncorrupted data. Fail loudly instead;
+	# tests corrupting small files must ensure real extents (btrfs:
+	# -o max_inline=0) or use an fs-specific corruption tool.
+	if ! $XFS_IO_PROG -r -c "fiemap" "$file" | grep -qE '\.\.'; then
+		_fail "_fsv_scratch_corrupt_bytes: '$file' has no fiemap extents (inline?); corruption would silently miss"
+	fi
+
 	cat > $tmp.bytes
 	local end=$(( offset + $(_get_filesize $tmp.bytes ) ))
 
